<subSubSection id="28CA7702E6699FCF78ADEE47EA343D9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="studied type specimens">
<paragraph id="5ABA020AC5B540AA7C44E05B9C58A5BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Studied type specimens.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F829E225F3F9E14C6785D29C57CC5BAB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Amazon Region • 1 ♂, holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="B3A2FC2E71F6D55C884C6BB0AEC818C2" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microdon aureoscutus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis id="A4EE850FD126BBF0080B626B607977B8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Microdon aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hull; Amazon; NHMUK. Label 1 (small, round, red-bordered): &quot;Holo- / type&quot;; label 2: &quot;Amazon / 6653&quot;; label 3 (red): &quot;Holotype / Microdon / aureoscutum / Hull&quot;. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="E35AC975E7D25239AC08C1AA4D1682CA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222934308527386" author="Hull, FM" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B12" refString="Hull, FM, 1943. .https://doi.org/10.1080/00222934308527386" url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222934308527386" year="1943">Hull (1943)</bibRefCitation>
this specimen was collected by H.W. Bates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8A287F526E52ECE9E13156A4394916FC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="EB00497F5FBB20CD8341DAB46C72E5FB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BFD3410B9FE38676135B5CE6E134D4FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 11 mm. The triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum places this species in a group together with 
<taxonomicName id="29FDA4830FC3E037E58B691F7638ED6A" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis id="CA2F09D91833B258FE41181AB267E860" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C5209842AF514DAB3370EA7A6AA25ED9" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="99C2B413241C5CF6879AAF140DD4EC36" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="09679A6D5FD4E99429F5B77BCFD13F2A" genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis id="06EB728523B07E7BFBB945C58057CEE8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From the latter two species, 
<taxonomicName id="2CFBEA2FCFF9B86C034DBB68CBF0CFB1" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis id="5A3B93CC98316B12D1E001F803EDC816" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the absence of golden pile along the anterior and lateral margins of the mesoscutum. The species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="BFCE92F6F953921A03DE5A1747B7F49C" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis id="B43B3370ABCA43AB52C831F29DFDB989" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum being wider than long and restricted to the posterior half of the mesoscutum. In the male, the ratio vertex width:head width is approximately 1:4.3 (
<figureCitation id="BA9F095A11B152BD65279CD801A2AE23" captionStart="Figures 19–24" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 19 - 24. 19, 20 Head dorsal: 19 Peradon aureoscutus male holotype (HW = head width, VW = vertex width) 20 P. aureus male Ecuador CNC 21 - 24 Tergite 2 dorsal: 21 Peradon aureoscutus male holotype 22 P. aureus male Ecuador CNC 23 P. trilinea male holotype 24 P. trivittatus male French Guiana RMNH." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures19-24" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362276" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures19-24">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
), and the lateral margins of tergite 2 are rather evenly diverging posteriad. Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation id="FC9D981A9AE13CCC9B95FFD22DE768A1" captionStart="Figures 256–261" captionStartId="F44" captionText="Figures 256 - 261. Male genitalia of Peradon species 256 P. fenestratus French Guyana MNHN 257 P. aureoscutus holotype 258 P. aureus Ecuador CNC 259 P. trilinea holotype 260 P. trivittatus Suriname RMNH 261 P. hermetia holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362314" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261">Fig. 257</figureCitation>
. The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
